## 3 Methods

The most common way of training biologically plausible RNNs involves simulating its dynamics using Euler's method for the forward pass (Figure 2A):

\[_{t+ t}_{t}+_{t}}{dt} t\] (5)

Here, \( t\) is the discretization time step that plays a central role in performing backpropagation through time on the simulated dynamics. Consequently, iterating this over \(\) time steps results in:

\[_{t+ t}^{}_{t}+_{k= 0}^{-1}_{t+k t}}{dt} t\] (6)

which we will denote as the dynamics of the base model \(_{t+ t}^{}\). We explore several ways in which this process can be modified, only during training, in order to help with the learning of long-term dependencies.

### Coarsened discretization (CD)

CD begins by training the network with a large step size to support stable gradients while learning long-term dependencies (Figure 2B). Here, (5) is modified to:

\[_{t+ t}^{}_{t}+_{t}}{dt} t\] (7)

for some discretization factor \(>1\). Thereafter, \(\) is gradually reduced over the course of training until \(=1\) at the end of training, resulting in a reversion to the base model described by (5).

### Skip connections through time (SCTT)

SCTT similarly confines the well-established idea of skip connections through time to training only (Figure 2C). For some mixing ratio \(\), a skip connection between time steps \(t\) and \(t+\) alters the hidden state as:

\[_{t+ t}^{}(1-)\,_{t }+\,_{t+ t}^{}\] (8)

The skip length \(\) remains unchanged throughout training, while the mixing ratio \(0< 1\) starts at a small value. This provides shortcuts for gradient backpropagation, thus reducing the risk of gradient instability. Similar to CD, the mixing is gradually reduced (i.e. \(\) is gradually increased to 1) until we are left with a trained network without skip connections (5).

### Dynamics-aligned skip connections (DASC)

We propose an additional method, DASC, which combines the essence of CD with SCTT, in order to respect dynamical properties of the system (Figure 2D). DASC achieves this by simulating large time steps through its skip connections. The skip connections between \(t\) and \(t+\) alters the hidden state as:

\[_{t+ t}^{}(1-)\,_{t + t}^{}+\,_{t+ t}^{}\] (9)

DASC aims to combine the benefits of CD and SCTT while limiting the risk of gradient instability. Unlike CD, DASC simultaneously trains the model with large and appropriately small time steps; unlike SCTT, it mitigates misalignment in the network's dynamics when it mixes hidden state estimates through the paths with and without skip connections.

